<BaseLayout
  title="What is problem gambling?"
  description="Problem gambling sits on a spectrum — and the line between concern, problem, and formal diagnosis is clearer when you know what DSM and ICD do and don't recognize."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/understand-gambling">← Understand gambling</a>
      </p>
      <h1>What is problem gambling?</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        "Problem gambling" is a broad term for gambling that's causing
        harm — to money, relationships, work, or health. Harm sits on a
        spectrum. You don't have to meet a clinical threshold, and you
        don't have to "hit bottom," to ask for help.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Gambling problems sit on a spectrum</h2>
      <p>
        Most people who gamble do so without harm. For some people,
        though, gambling starts to cause problems — with money,
        relationships, work, school, mood, or health.
      </p>
      <p>
        It helps to picture a spectrum rather than two boxes labeled
        "fine" and "addicted." Researchers often describe a range that
        looks something like this:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>No-risk or low-risk gambling</strong> — gambling
          that isn't causing harm.</li>
        <li><strong>At-risk gambling</strong> — early signs that
          gambling <em>could</em> become a problem.</li>
        <li><strong>Problem gambling</strong> — gambling that is already
          harming a person's life.</li>
        <li><strong>Gambling disorder</strong> — the most serious end,
          where the pattern meets a clinical diagnosis.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The point of the spectrum is simple: harm is not all-or-nothing.
        A person can be hurt by gambling long before they reach the most
        severe end.
      </p>

      <h3>"Problem gambling" is a broad term</h3>
      <p>
        "Problem gambling" is used as a wide, inclusive term. It covers
        gambling that is damaging to a person or their family —
        disrupting daily life, finances, work, or relationships — even
        when it does not meet the formal threshold for a clinical
        diagnosis (National Council on Problem Gambling).
      </p>
      <p>
        In other words, you can have a real gambling problem without
        having a diagnosed disorder. The harm is what matters, not
        whether a label fits perfectly.
      </p>

      <h3>You don't have to "hit bottom"</h3>
      <p>
        There's an old idea that a person has to lose everything before
        their gambling "counts." That isn't true, and it isn't helpful.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because harm builds up along a spectrum, help can make a
        difference at any point — including early, before things feel
        like a crisis. You don't have to wait. You don't have to be sure
        it's "bad enough."
      </p>
      <p>
        We also try to talk about people, not labels. A person <em>
        experiencing</em> gambling harm is still a whole person. Words
        like "addict" or "degenerate" add shame, and shame is one of the
        things that keeps people from reaching out.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you or someone you love is struggling, you can call or text
        <strong>1-800-MY-RESET</strong>
        (<a href="tel:18006973738">1-800-697-3738</a>) to talk through
        options. If anyone is in crisis or thinking about suicide, you
        can call, text, or chat <a href="tel:988">988</a> to reach the
        <strong>988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline</strong>.
      </p>

      <h2>What "diagnosis," DSM, and ICD mean</h2>
      <p>
        Before we get into the formal labels, here are the basics in
        plain language.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>A "diagnosis" is a clinical decision.</strong> It means a
        trained professional — such as a doctor, psychologist, or
        licensed counselor — has carefully assessed a person and
        concluded that their experience matches a recognized condition.
        A website, a quiz, or a worried family member can raise
        <em>concern</em>, but only a qualified professional can make an
        actual diagnosis.
      </p>
      <p>
        To stay consistent, professionals use shared manuals that
        describe each condition and list the signs used to identify it.
        Two manuals are used most:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>The DSM</strong> — the <em>Diagnostic and Statistical
          Manual of Mental Disorders</em>. It is published by the
          American Psychiatric Association and is used mainly in the
          United States. The current edition is the DSM-5-TR ("TR" means
          "text revision").
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The ICD</strong> — the <em>International Classification
          of Diseases</em>. It is published by the World Health
          Organization (WHO) and is used worldwide to record and report
          health conditions. The current edition is the ICD-11.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These manuals don't always line up perfectly. A condition can be
        official in one and not the other. That's exactly what we see
        with gambling, gaming, and screen time — so let's look at each.
      </p>

      <h2>The formal diagnoses: what exists and what doesn't</h2>

      <h3>Gambling — a recognized diagnosis in both manuals</h3>
      <p>
        Gambling has a formal, established diagnosis in <em>both</em>
        the DSM and the ICD.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>In the DSM-5-TR: Gambling Disorder.</strong> This is a
        notable milestone. Gambling Disorder was the <strong>first
        behavioral addiction</strong> included in the DSM. In earlier
        editions it was filed under "impulse-control disorders," but it
        was moved to sit alongside substance use disorders, in the group
        called "Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders." That move
        reflected research showing gambling can affect the brain's
        reward system in ways similar to addictive substances (American
        Psychiatric Association, 2013; Petry et al., 2014).
      </p>
      <p>
        The DSM-5-TR lists <strong>nine</strong> signs of Gambling
        Disorder. In plain language, a person may:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Need to gamble with more and more money to get the same
          excitement.</li>
        <li>Feel restless or irritable when trying to cut down or stop.</li>
        <li>Make repeated, unsuccessful efforts to control, cut back, or
          stop gambling.</li>
        <li>Spend a lot of time preoccupied with gambling — planning,
          reliving, or finding money to gamble.</li>
        <li>Gamble when feeling distressed — for example, anxious, sad,
          or guilty.</li>
        <li>Return another day to win back losses ("chasing" losses).</li>
        <li>Lie to hide how much they gamble.</li>
        <li>Risk or lose an important relationship, job, or school or
          career opportunity because of gambling.</li>
        <li>Rely on others for money to deal with desperate financial
          situations caused by gambling.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        A diagnosis is based on how many of these signs a person shows
        over a 12-month period, and severity is described in levels:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mild:</strong> 4–5 of the signs.</li>
        <li><strong>Moderate:</strong> 6–7 of the signs.</li>
        <li><strong>Severe:</strong> 8–9 of the signs.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These thresholds are tools for trained professionals — they
        aren't a self-test, and counting your own "signs" is not the
        same as a diagnosis.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>In the ICD-11: Gambling Disorder (code 6C50).</strong>
        The WHO's manual also recognizes gambling. It describes Gambling
        Disorder as a pattern of gambling — online or offline — marked
        by three core features: <strong>impaired control</strong> over
        gambling; <strong>giving gambling increasing priority</strong>
        so that it takes precedence over other interests and daily
        activities; and <strong>continuing or escalating</strong>
        gambling despite negative consequences. The pattern causes
        significant distress or harm to important areas of life, and is
        normally evident for at least 12 months (though that can be
        shorter if the symptoms are severe) (World Health Organization,
        n.d.).
      </p>
      <p>
        The ICD-11 also notes whether gambling happens mostly in person
        or mostly online, using specifiers:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Gambling disorder, predominantly offline (6C50.0)</strong>
          — gambling that is <em>not</em> mainly over the internet.</li>
        <li><strong>Gambling disorder, predominantly online (6C50.1)</strong>
          — gambling that is mainly over the internet.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The takeaway: for gambling, the diagnosis is well established
        and recognized in both the U.S. (DSM) and worldwide (ICD).
      </p>

      <h3>Gaming (video games) — recognized by WHO, still debated in the DSM</h3>
      <p>
        Video gaming is a different story, and it's worth being precise.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>In the ICD-11: Gaming Disorder (code 6C51) — a
        recognized diagnosis.</strong> The WHO added Gaming Disorder to
        the ICD-11. It describes a pattern of gaming behavior with the
        same three core features used for gambling: impaired control,
        increasing priority, and continuation despite negative
        consequences. For a diagnosis, the pattern must be serious
        enough to cause significant harm and would normally be evident
        for at least 12 months. The WHO stresses that gaming disorder
        affects only a small share of people who play games — most
        people who game are not at risk (World Health Organization).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>In the DSM: "Internet Gaming Disorder" — <em>not</em> an
        official diagnosis.</strong> The DSM-5 mentions Internet Gaming
        Disorder, but only in <strong>Section III</strong> — the part of
        the manual reserved for "conditions for further study." That
        means it is <em>not</em> an official DSM diagnosis. The American
        Psychiatric Association listed it there to encourage more
        research, because experts did not yet agree that the evidence
        and criteria were settled (American Psychiatric Association,
        2013).
      </p>
      <p>
        So the two manuals currently differ: the WHO recognizes Gaming
        Disorder, while the DSM still treats gaming as a condition that
        needs more study. Experts continue to debate how best to define
        it (Saunders et al., 2017).
      </p>

      <h3>Screen time, internet use, and smartphones — no formal diagnosis</h3>
      <p>
        Here it's important to be careful and not overstate things.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is currently <strong>no formal DSM or ICD diagnosis</strong>
        for general "screen time," "internet addiction," or "smartphone
        addiction." These are not recognized disorders in either manual.
      </p>
      <p>
        That does not mean the concern isn't real. Some people do feel
        that their phone, social media, or general internet use is hard
        to control and is interfering with sleep, school, work, or
        relationships. Researchers and clinicians study these patterns,
        and they have created screening questionnaires to measure them
        (Fineberg et al., 2018). But studying a pattern, and naming it a
        recognized diagnosis, are two different things — and the science
        isn't there yet for a single, agreed-upon disorder.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's also worth noting what the existing labels do <em>not</em>
        cover. The DSM's "Internet Gaming Disorder" entry is limited to
        internet gaming — it specifically does <strong>not</strong>
        include general internet use, online gambling, or social media.
        And the ICD's Gaming Disorder is about gaming, not screen time
        in general.
      </p>
      <p>
        So if you're worried about screen use, your concern is valid and
        worth taking seriously — but it would not currently be given a
        formal "diagnosis" in the way gambling can be.
      </p>

      <h2>These can overlap — and help is available</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling, gaming, and heavy screen use don't live in separate
        boxes. They can overlap, and any of them can occur alongside
        stress, anxiety, depression, or other challenges. A person might
        game and gamble; online gambling happens <em>on</em> a screen.
        That overlap is one reason it helps to understand the words
        clearly.
      </p>
      <p>
        Wherever a person sits on the spectrum — curious, at-risk, or
        struggling — understanding is a good first step, and so is
        reaching out. You don't need a diagnosis, and you don't need to
        "hit bottom," to ask a question or get support.
      </p>
      <p>
        For warning signs and a short, private self-check, see <a
        href="/understand-gambling/warning-signs-risk-factors">Warning
        signs &amp; risk factors</a>.
      </p>

